data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, the compiler's new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` on `int[]` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of the old `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

Expression trees **cannot represent span-based method calls** (`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct). So the expression either fails to compile or, if the tree is built dynamically, throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` so the compiler picks `Enumerable.Contains` again:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects **`Reverse()`** on arrays (now binds to the in-place `Span` version returning `void`). The fix pattern is identical — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` or `.AsEnumerable().Reverse()`.
